  "slug": "mille-feuille-vanilla",
  "title": "Mille-feuille",
  "subtitle": "Flaky rough puff layered with vanilla pastry cream and iced",
  "excerpt": "Three layers of shatteringly crisp rough puff pastry, two layers of thick vanilla pastry cream, and a white icing with a dark chocolate feather pattern on top. Rough puff replaces full puff without losing the blister and shatter. Serves six.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Mille-feuille is documented in French cuisine from the seventeenth century and codified in Auguste Escoffier, Le Guide Culinaire (1903), as a standard French pastry of puff pastry sheets layered with pastry cream and iced. The name meaning 'a thousand leaves' refers to the many layers of the pastry. The feather-icing decoration across the top is a standard technique documented in mid-twentieth-century French patisserie manuals. The recipe is fully public domain.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Mille-feuille is built on contrast: shattering crisp pastry against soft, cold ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "pastry cream",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpa9v4520000u0v4sxj4he6z"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": ". The ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "rough puff",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmp876lj50000b0v4nf1wbtdp"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " used here gives excellent results in a fraction of the time of full puff. The layers are not as numerous or as even, but they blister and shatter the same way when baked correctly. The key step is pressing the sheets flat with a second tray halfway through baking. This stops the pastry puffing too dramatically and gives clean, stackable sheets.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Assemble close to serving. The pastry softens within a couple of hours of contact with the cream and loses its crispness. Bake the pastry and make the cream ahead, then assemble shortly before eating.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Ingredients",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "ingredientsList",
        "content": [
          {
